itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-28-boat-neck-corset-with-two-princess-seams/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-28-boat-neck-corset-with-two-princess-seams/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-12-02T13:22:16+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-12-02T13:22:16+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 28. Boat-Neck Corset with Two Princess Seams."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 28. Boat-Neck Corset with Two Princess Seams."><meta itemprop="description" content="This tutorial was made for all who wish to delve into the anatomy of corset patterns and find out how my pattern was constructed."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 28. Boat-Neck Corset with Two Princess Seams.</h1><p><strong>This tutorial was made for all who wish to delve into the anatomy of corset patterns and find out how my pattern was constructed. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p>I will not go through all stages of making this pattern because I made it about 20 years ago. But I will tell you about the key steps.</p><p><strong>As I mentioned before, my corset pattern is based on a pattern of a multi-part corset cup. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>The pattern of a multi-part cup is made based on a certain algorithm.</strong> This algorithm is not a secret and you can find it in all textbooks used at dressmaking and sewing schools, as well as on many free online platforms.</p><p>It is a lot harder to turn it into a pattern which will be suitable for a wide range of sizes, i.e. easily adjustable in accordance with my method. Moreover, it is particularly hard to make a corset pattern combinable with the technique of putting bones in the cups offered in my courses.</p><p><strong>My pattern was made specifically to be used with this technique. </strong></p><p><strong>But if you adjust it, for example, for a plump woman, then an under-bust dart will arise. </strong>Not everyone understands why this happens because I had thought it was enough to recommend you should make this dart and never explained the reasons. I never focused on the anatomic origin of this dart and skipped all purely construction-related details to keep my courses understandable for beginners, as well as for people who are used to just sewing after a ready pattern. These people usually don’t care how the pattern was made, let alone how it was tried and brought to perfection.</p><p><strong>All standard patterns offered at the Corset Academy were made years ago. I have been using them for decades without changing anything. </strong>During the first two years after I made these patterns, I was trying them out and bringing them to perfection by applying literally half-a-millimeter adjustments. And as soon as I realized they worked perfectly, I stopped applying any further changes. Of course, I do make new patterns of new corsets and dresses based on these initial ones, but the foundation stays the same!</p><p><strong>The Corset Academy launched its online courses in 2010, and my patterns started spreading widely across the Internet. </strong>Over 10 million people had watched my video tutorials and used my patterns on my Russian-language YouTube channel by the early 2017, and about as many on the English-language channel. And so I can say it with confidence that my patterns have been acclaimed and are successfully used by hundreds of thousands of dressmakers!</p><p><strong>But I must warn you against one thing! </strong>Lately, there have been many fee-based online sewing courses popping up on various Internet web-sites where private dressmakers invite you to learn how to sew wedding and evening garments cut after my patterns and offer my patterns together with their guidelines. I am glad that many of these people give honest credit and say that the patterns were made by the Corset Academy and even leave our logo on them. Of course, there are also some teachers who claim that the patterns they use were made by them personally. The problem is not that they do plagiarism - let it be on their conscience. The problem is that they start giving their students very harmful advice having no idea how these patterns were made! For example, they call nonsense my warnings against changing the bust princess seams, and they think they have a right for it! But they cannot answer why one must not change the bust princess seams because they did not create these patterns and they simply don’t have enough knowledge of them.</p><p>In reality, there are very solid grounds behind my warnings! I will show you how I calculated the width of under-bust darts for this particular standard patterns, and you will see that I am right in saying you must not change the configuration of the bust princess seams!</p><p><strong>Suppose we have made a pattern of a multi-part corset cup and now we need to create a pattern of a corset with integrated cups based on it. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>As I said before, the multi-part cup is made of three main pieces: top piece (1), centre bottom piece (2), and side bottom piece (3). </strong></p><p><strong>Parts of the cup overlap with bridge pieces. </strong>It is impossible to avoid this overlap no matter how you position the cup pieces.</p><p><strong>And it is what affects the under-bust dart width. </strong></p><p><strong>After splitting the top cup piece (1) in two pieces ((1.1) and (1.2)), i.e. adding a bust princess seam, I try to close the central dart between pieces (1) and (2). </strong></p><p><strong>But piece (1.1) has a straight edge</strong>, which means I can only close the central dart as far as this straight edge allows considering it should be positioned vertically, i.e. parallel to the fold line of the centre front corset piece.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>As the result, the central dart remains open. </strong></p><p><strong>And what will happen in this case? </strong>If the central dart remains open, there will be no depression formed between the cups. This is acceptable for boat-neck or strapless corsets but absolutely inappropriate for a low V-neck corset which requires a snug fit along the middle of the bust. And this depression between the cups will only arise when the central dart is fully closed.</p><p><strong>The central dart issue can be illustrated more clearly if I transfer pieces (1.1) and (2) on the centre front corset piece together with the bridge. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p>You can clearly see that the central dart is rather deep<strong> now that these pieces are positioned on the centre front corset piece with regard to 1.2cm seam allowances.</strong></p><p>Looking at the dart right now, you can already imagine how much fabric needs to be taken in near the bust line to form a depression between the cups.</p><p><strong>Please remember that my pattern with seamlessly integrated cups was made with account for bones in the cups.</strong> Those who are familiar with the Corset Academy courses know that you often form a rather deep under-bust dart when pressing cups with bones, with an opening of 1.5-2.5cm depending on garment size.</p><p><strong>I suppose now you understand where this under-bust dart comes from? </strong>When we slightly ease in the lining of the corset in the process of putting a half-circle central Rigilene bone on the cup to give it a proper round shape, we simultaneously reduce the width of the central dart and cause an under-bust dart to get formed automatically. Its width fully corresponds with the width by which the central dart was reduced.</p><p><strong>This is why an under-bust dart always emerges on the lining of a corset cut one piece with cups. </strong></p><p><strong>I transfer the side bottom cup piece (3) and the adjoining bridge piece on the side front corset piece. </strong>I try to align the cup piece and the bridge piece as well as I can, but they still overlap under the bust.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I transfer the remaining top cup piece (1.2) on the side front corset piece and position it parallel to the princess seam.&nbsp; </strong></p><p><strong>Please note that the side dart is only partially closed in this position! </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Many years ago, when I was working on this pattern, I naturally wanted to get this side dart closed properly. </strong>And I tried to achieve perfect alignment with the bridge at the same time.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Meanwhile, </strong>my princess seam line went at a very big angle to the vertical axis starting from the bust area, i.e. the bust dart was very deep and the cups basically lay horizontally and acquired an odd shape.</p><p><strong>It took me a long time to figure out why all this happened despite the fact that the multi-part cup pattern had been made according to all rules.</strong></p><p><strong>And the answer literally lay on the surface: </strong>I was trying to turn low sew-in multi-part cups into high non-sew-in cups, i.e. cups cut one piece with the corset! And these are simply two different things!</p><p><strong>It took me some years of trial and error with my sleeves rolled up to find the right incline of the bust princess seam which would ensure a good fit in the bust and a graceful shape of the cups! </strong></p><p><strong>The side dart still remains though! </strong></p><p><strong>I made another important conclusion during all that work. </strong>The darts must not be straight but somewhat rounded to form beautiful 3-D cups on a corset.</p><p><strong>The round cup shape is also achieved by easing in the fabric when putting a half-circle Rigilene bone along the bottom border of the cup on the side corset pieces. </strong>The amount of easing-in reaches up to 10-15mm.</p><p><strong>Such easing-in solves another task apart from improving the shape of the cups: </strong>the side corset piece gets slightly lowered in the armscye, which ensures a better fit in this area.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2028.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>When I was making my standard corset patterns, I was simultaneously thinking over the sewing and cutting technique. </strong>I always connect the pattern and the sewing technique in my head in advance, or else it is impossible to make a beautiful garment.</p><p><strong>My standard pattern of a corset cut one piece with cups can be used for small sizes but, frankly speaking, it is better-suited for full-figured women. </strong>As you know, it provides for two darts (central dart and side dart) which you must either close or re-distribute following the methods described above: easing in the fabric under the half-circle bone along the border of the cup and forming under-bust darts on the centre front piece. <strong>But if your client has full breasts, </strong>you might not even have to use these methods or use them partially because the gapping at the top of the cups will get naturally filled in by the breast tissue and the corset will only look better. But since we don’t put a half-circle bone along the border of the cup and don’t ease in the fabric in this case, the side dart remains open and it is very hard to achieve a good fit along the neckline edge of the corset!</p><p><strong>Dressmakers tend to come up with various “ideas” how to change the princess seams at the top or under the bust to improve the fit in the chest. </strong>Most beginners think: “The neckline edge doesn’t cling to the bust. It must be the princess seams, I need to change them urgently!” And they start taking in the princess seams under the bust to press the corset closer to the body. <strong>This, however, results in the opposite effect: the cups start gapping even more because of too much tension under the bust. </strong></p><p><strong>I thought over the sewing technique when I was making this standard pattern. I thought over ways to reinforce the princess seams with Rigilene bones. </strong>The bone might not be able to support the cup if the princess seam is very curvy. Do a small research on the construction of historical corsets. Their bust princess seams are absolutely straight, not a slightest hint at 3-D cups! This was done purposely to hold the breasts up very firmly and not let them sink down. But such straight bust princess seams are so flat that they squeeze and flatten the chest quite badly. It is the reason why contemporary corset-makers don’t like historical corsets.</p><p><strong>When I was working on the shape of bust princess seams, I had to account for two mutually exclusive aspects: </strong>the curve of the bust princess seam must allow the bone to support the cup on the one hand and ensure a 3-D cup shape on the other hand. I had to find the golden mean in the shape of the princess seam line: make it just a little rounder and the bone will stop supporting the cup, break under its weight, and the cup will start gapping. And even an additional plastic bone will not help when your client has full breasts.</p><p><strong>My standard pattern of a boat-neck corset cut one piece with cups was made and perfected with regard to all these aspects. Every line, every dart was tried on hundreds of clients. </strong>I am happy to share it with you and I am absolutely sure your work will be a great success as long as you use it correctly and follow my recommendations - recommendations of their author.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<stron